The setup with 9 detectors was realized,
which provided the tightest possible arrangement.  The
detectors were HPGe detectors surrounded by individual
active shields made of BGO scintillators.  The distance
of any detector to the center of the target was about
13 cm.  The relative efficiency of each of the nine
detectors was typically 70% compared to a standard
3-inch X 3-inch NaI detector.
The 4He+-beam intensity was in the range
100-340 muA.  The runs at voltages above 3.3 MeV had
to be carried out with reduced beam currents.
experimental method

calculate relative phase shift from elastic

energy deconvolution method. Detailed reanalysis of
present data is given.
Enriched 12-C target. The target has been designed for
high beam powers of up to 10 kW/cm2. The backing
consists of a 2 mm thick copper plate with 14 one mm
diameter cooling channels covering an area of about
25X25 mm2. Cooling water flowed at about 25 m/s with a
pressure of 50 bars.  The backing is soldered into a
stainless steel cylinder that enables connecting the
water and reversing the target without breaking vacuum.
The copper plate was plated with a layer of 20 mum
of high-purity gold, serving as the substrate for the
12-C implantation.
The estimation of the errors in the net
extracted yields were determined in the standard way
from the yield estimates of the total and background
counts. At low bombarding energy, when the peak
positions were not always visually clear, and to take
account of any small variation in the detector energy
calibration, an additional contribution to the error
was calculated by varying slightly the position and
width of the window around the expected values.
